intent: >
  Give the monitoring system a visible surface. GET /sites (and the root
  route) renders a dashboard table with name, URL, status badge, and
  relative last-checked timestamp for every monitored site.

slice: 7/8
kind: feature
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: reversible

scope:
  declared:
    - app/controllers/sites_controller.rb
    - app/views/sites/index.html.erb
    - app/views/sites/_status_badge.html.erb
    - spec/requests/sites_spec.rb
    - config/routes.rb
  actual:
    - app/controllers/sites_controller.rb
    - app/views/sites/index.html.erb
    - app/views/sites/_status_badge.html.erb
    - spec/requests/sites_spec.rb
    - config/routes.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/requests/sites_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop app/controllers/sites_controller.rb spec/requests/sites_spec.rb config/routes.rb
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "Inline styles are acceptable for the walking skeleton. A proper CSS strategy (Tailwind, Propshaft custom sheets, or component-level styles) lands in a future epic alongside site CRUD."
  - "has_many :check_results on Site is STILL deferred. The index view only reads Site columns (name, url, status, last_checked_at). The latest check detail (response_time_ms, error_message) belongs on a future detail page, not the index table."
  - "Request spec (not controller spec, not system spec). Request specs are the Rails 5+ standard for testing controller behavior without browser overhead. A system spec (Capybara + Selenium) would verify the rendered HTML more thoroughly but is overkill for a table of text."
  - "Site.order(:name) is the default sort. No pagination — an MVP with a handful of sites doesn't need it. At scale, add .page(params[:page]) with Kaminari or Pagy."

deviations_from_plan: none

trade_offs: >
  Inline styles in the ERB views rather than a stylesheet. Chose this
  because: (a) the walking skeleton is proving the data loop, not the
  design system, (b) extracting to a stylesheet now would set a CSS
  precedent before we've decided on the CSS strategy (Tailwind? plain
  Propshaft? component styles?), (c) inline styles are trivially
  grep-able and self-contained, which is right for a spike that will
  be restyled. The cost is obvious: no reuse, verbose markup, no
  hover/focus states. Future epic trades these for a real design
  system.

self_review:
  metz: >
    Controller is 4 lines total — 1 action, 1 instance variable, 0
    callbacks. Sandi's "controllers instantiate one object" is
    satisfied literally.
  consistency: >
    First controller in the repo. Pattern: one action, one AR query
    in the action, no before_action, no concerns, no helpers. Future
    controllers should match this shape until the complexity justifies
    extracting.
  security: >
    site.url is rendered inside a link_to with target _blank and rel
    noopener noreferrer. The URL is user-supplied (stored verbatim
    from Site creation), so it could be a javascript: URI. link_to
    does NOT sanitize the href value — it renders whatever string you
    pass. For the single-user MVP this is a self-inflicted risk (the
    user entered the URL). When multi-user lands, the link_to target
    needs a scheme allowlist (http/https only) or ERB-level
    sanitization. Flagged for the same future epic that addresses
    SSRF in HttpChecker (slice 3).
  performance: >
    Site.order(:name) with no pagination, no includes, no preloading.
    For a handful of sites this is a single query, no N+1. At scale,
    add pagination. If the view ever shows check_results data, add
    .includes(:check_results) to avoid N+1.

confidence: high

reviewer_attention:
  - app/views/sites/index.html.erb:25         # link_to with user-supplied URL — javascript: URI risk on multi-user
  - app/views/sites/_status_badge.html.erb:1-8 # color mapping — extracted partial for reuse
